{"key":"post-8730730","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8730730</id>\n<content>My experience is that it's far easier to maintain high humidity with proper air exchange by placing the unit inside the greenhouse, and then cutting windows and slits for FAE.&amp;nbsp; The windows ensure that the interior never gets stale, and the coolmist recycling humid air increases humidity over the one-pass method you get when piping it in.&amp;nbsp;  In addition, adding hoses and/or blocking the natural output causes static pressure which ruins the bushings sooner, resulting in motor failure as it loads down.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It took a few years and a huge pile of wasted vics humidifiers to learn that lesson.&amp;nbsp; With the unit inside the greenhouse, it will last much longer.&amp;nbsp; Use a timer and dial it in so you get maximum humidity with as little water on the sides and floor as possible.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8730743</next>\n<prev>8730695</prev>\n<first>8719223</first>\n<last>8731256</last>\n<when>1217986175</when>\n<utime>08/06/08 04:29 AM</utime>\n</post>"}